<section class="section bg-cream">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header centered">
            <span class="section-eyebrow">SDI in Corn</span>
            <h2>How Subsurface Drip Changes Corn Economics</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="three-col-grid">
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🌽</div>
                <h3>Split Nitrogen Delivery</h3>
                <p>Corn's nitrogen demand peaks at V6, V10, and VT/R1. SDI fertigation lets you split N applications to precisely match these stages, improving NUE by 30–40% and eliminating early-season over-application.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🌡️</div>
                <h3>Silking-Stage Protection</h3>
                <p>Water stress during the 8-day silking/pollination window causes irreversible yield losses. SDI provides exact soil moisture control at this critical stage — the single most important irrigation event of the season.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">⚡</div>
                <h3>Half the Pumping Energy</h3>
                <p>SDI systems for corn operate at lower pressure than pivot systems. Combined with lower total water volume, pumping energy costs drop by 45–55% — a $40–$90/acre annual operating savings.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🚜</div>
                <h3>Field Accessibility</h3>
                <p>Unlike center pivots, SDI systems do not obstruct field operations. Side-dress passes, scouting, and aerial applications can be done at any time without pivots blocking access.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">📏</div>
                <h3>Uniform Stand Establishment</h3>
                <p>SDI can be pulsed to maintain consistent seed zone moisture at planting and through V3, dramatically improving emergence uniformity — the single largest driver of final yield in corn.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="highlight-card">
                <div class="highlight-card-icon">📊</div>
                <h3>Case Study: Western Kansas</h3>
                <p>A 1,800-acre corn operation replaced a center pivot with SDI and cut water applications from 18" to 9" per season, reducing total input costs by $82/acre while increasing average yield from 210 to 238 bu/acre.</p>
                <a href="/growers-stories" class="btn-primary-sm" style="margin-top:16px;">Read Case Studies →</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

